In an Appendix to the text is printed “ A Boon: or SURVEIGHE: and an abstract out of the rentale of au the Landes Tenementes and Revenews that belongs to the Cathedrall' Churche of Durism' with the perfect and perticuler State theros mayd anno Reginae Elizabethae vicissimo secund0, 158 0.''

The original MS. from which this Survey is printed is also preserved in the Treasury of the Dean and Chapter of Durham. In the Survey will be found au the vills mentioned in the Halmote Rolls, besides many other places from which the Dean and Chapter derived their revenues, not mentioned in the Bous, and presumably in no way connected with the Halmote Court. This valuable and interesting record throws much light on the relations of the then recently founded Dean and Chapter towards their tenantS, as compared with the relations we have seen existing between the Prior and the tenants of the conventual body.
